            "answer_text": "Whichever one is presenting the greater hazard to traffic safety. If one\u2019s going 73 in a 65 in an open fast lane, while another\u2019s going 90 and weaving around traffic through all lanes, the 90mph offender is the greater threat, and somewhat cynically, the more expensive and harder-to-fight ticket.Whichever one he guns first. If both cars are at a totally unsafe speed (e.g. 90 in a 65), he will gun one of them, see that car is way over the speed limit, and start preparations to pull that car over. The other car, he won\u2019t know its exact speed and so won\u2019t have the probable cause to pull it over. No matter, he got one of them, and if the other person keeps driving like that he won\u2019t get far.Both. The officer doesn\u2019t have to get in his vehicle and chase down a violator; if he sees you coming far enough away, all he has to do is signal you to pull over from where he stands on the side of the road. He can do that to both cars. If he sees that you see him and you do not pull over, that\u2019s evading detention or arrest which can be a felony in some states because you\u2019re doing so in a motor vehicle. All he has to do is take down your plate, make, model and a brief description of you (gender, approximate age, race, hair color) to single you out from among potential registered drivers of that vehicle, and bingo, you now have a warrant for your arrest.In addition, many speed traps are run with more than one vehicle, forming a gun and chase team. If there\u2019s more than one vehicle on hand to find and chase down speeders, then either two chase vehicles or the chaser and the gunner will pick a car each and pull it over.Neither. If the cars are going a moderate amount over the speed limit (<10mph) and not posing any other imminent hazard to other drivers like weaving or tailgating, the officer might let both of them go and look for a driver behaving badly enough that the ticket will be more warranted (and harder to fight).",
