            "answer_text": "The details in your question present an unrealistic scenario for any enforcement activity. If the officer is using radar to verify speed, s/he shouldn\u2019t be checking two cars running side-by-side.+4 and +9 don\u2019t provide much in the way of an obvious enough difference in speed to say \u201cThat car is fastest\u201d without something to verify speed.Even if there\u2019s a hard-and-fast speed limit, +4 and +9 won\u2019t pique the interest of most officers.Now.. change your scenario a bit and it all becomes, \u201cIt depends.\u201d If one car is running +14 on the highway and the second is a few hundred yards behind the first running +19, it might just be whichever car is at the rear when the officer catches up. Or, the officer may choose the fastest car. If one car is running steadily in a lane and signaling lane changes, but the second is herky-jerking left and right, trying to exploit every possible lane opening for that extra foot of space, you can bet your sweet bippy I\u2019ll go after the second car. Or, the red car. (Just kidding\u2026 Why do red cars get more speeding tickets?) ",
