            },
            "answer_text": "I agree with Christopher Hawk\u2019s answer: it depends. I\u2019ve noticed that people on Quora frequently want to believe that there is a standard, consistent playbook for all law enforcement officers in the United States. This is not remotely true. Every one of the 50 states has a different basic and in-service training requirement. Of those states, most provide law enforcement training through multiple law enforcement academies run by individual law enforcement agencies, community colleges, tech schools, or the state training agency itself. The curriculum for any one of those academies may change from class to class, depending on who is available to teach. Further, each officer has considerable discretion on when and in what circumstances he will make a traffic stop. One of my academy classmates was proud of the fact that he had served ten years, and had still not used up the book of 25 traffic citation blanks we had been issued in the academy. Patrol officers were under zero pressure to write citations. An officer assigned to a purely traffic function might be more inclined to make stops. Even then, he will have days he works aggressively, and others where he finds other things to fill his time. So, to sum up: Either. Both. Neither. If you don\u2019t want to get stopped, don\u2019t exceed the posted speed limit. ",
