        {
            "author_info": {
                "name": "Daniel Wallander",
                "href": "/profile/Daniel-Wallander"
            },
            "answer_text": "I asked a Wisconsin Highway Patrol officer once which car in a line of speeding cars would he choose to stop, if he chose to stop only one of the cars. He said, he just turns on his lights and tickets the one who pulls over. For your question, he would most likely pull over the more egregious speeder, but he could pull over either or both as both are speeding. The 3 mph over speeder is going to ask why me? The cop is going to say, you were speeding. The judge is going to ask if you were speeding and you will truthfully answer yes, the judge says guilty. That there was a more egregious speeder at the same time is irrelevant. ",
